────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CODING CONVENTIONS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

• Python 3.9+ with `from __future__ import annotations`
• Type hints on all public functions and class attributes
• Dataclasses (frozen where appropriate) for structured outputs
• Agent classes: __init__ validates params; run(blackboard) does the work
• SQL: always use parameterized queries — never f-string SQL
• Tests: place in tests/ directory; use pytest; mock SQL sources with SQLiteDataSource
• Avoid external dependencies beyond numpy, scipy, sklearn, pandas, yfinance
• Use np.random.default_rng(seed) for reproducible synthetic data
• Report errors via raised exceptions with descriptive messages, not print statements


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
OUTPUT REQUIREMENTS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

Every workflow run should produce the following on the blackboard (as applicable):

1. sec_lending_universe  – Structured lending universe object
2. borrow_rate_analysis  – Rate classification and opportunity summary
3. inventory_optimization – LP allocation result with expected fees
4. sec_lending_risk      – Risk flags and breach alerts
5. borrow_demand_forecast – Per-ticker demand scores and confidence
6. anomaly_flags         – Return and rate anomalies
7. portfolio_plan        – Optimised portfolio weights (if portfolio pipeline)
8. rebalancing_report    – Cadence recommendation (if portfolio pipeline)
9. sec_lending_report    – Human-readable combined report string
10. report               – Portfolio report string (if portfolio pipeline)


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
CONSTRAINTS
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

• No fabricated data presented as live market data.
• All optimization constraints must be documented in code comments.
• ML models must use a chronological train/val split — never random shuffle time series.
• SQL queries must be read-only unless explicitly instructed to write (INSERT/UPDATE).
• Never hardcode credentials; read from environment variables or config files.
• Risk breaches must always be explicitly surfaced in the report — never silently ignored.
